	<p>
		<table xml:id="LT-Diagram">
		<tabular>
			<col halign="center" valign="middle" />
			<col halign="center" valign="middle" />
			<col halign="center" valign="middle" />
			<row>
				<cell><m>y'' + 5y' - 6y = e^{3t}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\large \overset{\Large \lap}{\underset{\text{forward}}{\longrightarrow}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ds s^2Y + 5sY - 6Y = \frac{1}{s-3}</m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell/>
				<cell/>
				<cell><m>|</m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell/>
				<cell/>
				<cell><m>\text{Solve for } Y</m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell/>
				<cell/>
				<cell><m>\downarrow</m></cell>
			</row>
			<row>
				<cell><m>y = e^{2t} + e^{t} - 2e^{3t}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\large \overset{\Large \lap^{-1}}{\underset{\text{backward}}{\longleftarrow}}</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\ds Y = \frac{1}{s-3} + \frac{1}{s-1} + \frac{-2}{s-4}</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</table>
	</p>

	<p>
		Before we solve any DEs with this new solution technique, we need to practice the pieces of the solution technique. Thus, we dedicate the next couple of sections on learning what the Laplace transform is, how to find the Laplace transform of a function, and how to take the inverse Laplace transform of a function. Then we will finally be solve DEs using this new solution technique.
	</p>

